{{Infobox language |name=Burji |states=[[Ethiopia]], [[Kenya]] |region=South of [[Lake Chamo]] |speakers=70,000 |date=2007 & 2009 censuses |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] |fam3=[[Highland East Cushitic languages|Highland East]] |script=Ethiopic |iso3=bji |glotto=burj1242 |glottorefname=Burji }}
'''Burji language''' (alternate names: ''Bembala, Bambala, Daashi'') is an [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] language spoken by the [[Burji people]] who reside in [[Ethiopia]] south of [[Lake Chamo]]. There are over 46,000 speakers in Ethiopia, and a further 10,400 speakers in [[Kenya]]. Burji belongs to the [[Highland East Cushitic]] group of the [[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] branch of the [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] family.<ref name=e18/>
The language has the SOV (subject–object–verb) word order common to the Cushitic family. The verb morphology distinguishes passive and middle [[grammatical voice]], as well as causative. Verbal suffixes mark the person, number, and gender of the subject.
The New Testament was published in the Burji language in 1993. A collection of Burji proverbs, translated into English, French, and Swahili, is available on the Web.<ref>Angelique Chelo. 2016. A COLLECTION OF 100 BURJI PROVERBS AND WISE SAYINGS. [http://www.afriprov.org/images/stories/ebooks/burji.pdf Web Access]</ref>
