{{distinguish|Mao language|Southern Mao language}} {{Infobox language family |name=Mao |region=[[Ethiopia]] |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Omotic languages|Omotic]] |glotto=maoo1243 |glottorefname=Mao }}
The '''Mao languages''' are a branch of the [[Omotic languages]] spoken in [[Ethiopia]]. The group had the following categories: *[[Bambassi language|Bambasi]], spoken in the [[Bambasi]] [[woreda]] of [[Benishangul-Gumuz Region]], *[[Hozo language|Hozo]] and [[Seze language|Seze]] (often described together as 'Begi Mao'), spoken around [[Beica|Begi]] in the [[Mirab Welega Zone|Mirab (West) Welega Zone]] of the [[Oromia Region]], and *[[Ganza language|Ganza]], which is spoken south of [[Bambasi]] in the [[Asosa Zone]] of Benishangul-Gumuz Region and west of the Hozo and Seze languages.
It is estimated that there are 5,000 speakers of Bambasi, 3,000 speakers each of Hozo and Seze and a few hundred Ganza speakers (Bender, 2000). During recent political upheavals, a few thousand Bambassi speakers established themselves in the valley of the [[Didessa River]] and [[Belo Jegonfoy]] [[woreda]]. Much of the Mirab Welega Zone was once the home of Mao languages, but they have lost speakers because of the increasing influence of [[Oromo language|Oromo]].
